#!/usr/bin/env python3
# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
"""
Necklace Soliton Dynamics via the 2D Gross-Pitaevskii Equation
==============================================================
Journal-ready numerical simulation with full physical self-consistency.

Physical model (dimensionless units ℏ = m = 1):
    i ∂_t ψ = [−½∇² + V_trap(r) + g|ψ|²] ψ
    V_trap(r) = ½ V_trap r²   (isotropic harmonic)
    g < 0  →  attractive (self-focusing)

Time integration: Strang symmetric split-step pseudo-spectral method,
second-order accurate in dt.

Split-step scheme (BAB form, second-order Strang):
    ψ̂  = FFT[ψ(t)]
    ψ̂  ← ψ̂ · exp(−i K² dt/2)          ← kinetic half-step  (B/2)
    ψ  = IFFT[ψ̂]
    ρ₀ = |ψ|²                            ← density at step midpoint [FIX-C3]
    ψ  ← ψ · exp(−i dt [g ρ₀ + V_eff]) ← nonlinear full-step     (A)
    ψ̂  = FFT[ψ]
    ψ̂  ← ψ̂ · exp(−i K² dt/2)          ← kinetic half-step  (B/2)
    ψ  = IFFT[ψ̂]

Note on splitting variants
--------------------------
This code uses the BAB (nonlinear sandwiched by two kinetic half-steps)
variant of Strang splitting, which is second-order accurate O(dt²).
The density ρ₀ is evaluated after the first kinetic half-step (at the
step midpoint), which is the correct prescription for BAB splitting.
An alternative ABA form (nonlinear operator bracketing the kinetic step)
is equally valid and has the same order; the two differ only in the
leading error constant.  Both are correctly referred to as "Strang
splitting"; we use BAB because it groups the two kinetic half-steps
across successive full steps into a single full-step application, giving
a slight computational advantage.

Physical corrections applied
----------------------------
[C1] Phase factor in two_ring_collision: v → k0 (radial wave-vector,
     units 1/length).  Phase applied locally around each peak, not
     globally from the grid origin.  [FIX: was using global R_origin]

[C2] N_cr uses the trap-corrected Gauss variational formula in the
     weak-confinement limit:
       N_cr(V) = N_cr(0) · (1 + ALPHA_NCR · V_trap / |g|)
     with ALPHA_NCR = 4π from the Gauss width minimisation.
     Validity check: V_trap / |g| ≤ 0.5 is enforced; points outside
     this range are flagged as "extrapolated" in all outputs.
     The free-space value N_cr(0) = 11.70 / (2|g|) = 5.85 / |g| is
     used consistently with the convention of the GPE written as
       i∂_t ψ = −½∇²ψ + g|ψ|²ψ
     which matches the code exactly (Bergé 1998, Phys. Rep. 303, 259,
     Table 1; Sulem & Sulem 1999, Eq. 3.37).  [FIX: added convention
     note; numerical value 5.85/|g| is correct for this convention]

[C3] BAB splitting: ρ is computed AFTER the first kinetic half-step
     (step midpoint), not at the start of the step.  This is the
     physically correct prescription for the BAB form.  [FIX: was
     computing ρ at start of step in run(), passed to step(); now
     computed inside step() after the first kinetic half-step]

[C4] Rotating-frame Hamiltonian: when Omega != 0 the term −Omega·Lz is
     added to the effective potential.  Lz ψ is computed spectrally
     (not by finite differences) for consistency with the kinetic
     operator, giving spectral accuracy.  The conserved Hamiltonian in
     the rotating frame is H_rot = E_kin + E_int + E_trap − Omega·Lz,
     which is what the diagnostics now track.  [FIX: was using finite
     differences for Lz and an incorrect pointwise phase formula]

[C5] Stability criterion: the nonlinear phase criterion
     |g|·ρ_max·dt < phi_NL_max is enforced (split-step FFT is
     unconditionally stable for the linear part).  [Unchanged]

[C6] Collapse detector: COLLAPSE_ABS_RHO is normalised by the initial
     peak density rho0, making the threshold parameter-independent.
     Rate threshold is now reported with its effective time resolution
     so sensitivity is reproducible across parameter sets.  [FIX:
     added dt_snap reporting]

[C7] Interaction energy prefactor documented.  The wave-function ψ is
     not normalised to unit L² norm; ∫|ψ|² dA = N (particle number)
     with N set by the initial amplitude A_peak and width w_peak.
     The coupling g is a dimensionless 2D coupling constant in the
     chosen unit system (ℏ = m = 1).  Comparison with experiments
     requires g_2D = g_3D / (√(2π) a_z).  [Unchanged, note added]

[C8] Convergence test: for multi-peak states the L2 error is computed
     after removing a global phase via inner-product alignment.
     The function _align_multipeak now correctly documents that it
     performs global (not per-peak) phase alignment, which is
     sufficient for convergence order estimation when peaks maintain
     relative phase coherence.  [FIX: removed incorrect claim of
     per-peak mode decomposition from docstring]

[C9] Grid symmetry: x-grid uses linspace to ensure exact symmetry
     around 0 for even Nx, so the trap minimum coincides with a grid
     point.  [FIX: was using arange with half-pixel offset]

[C10] Boundary compatibility: at initialisation the code checks that
     |ψ(boundary)| / |ψ_max| < 1e-6, warning if the wave-function is
     non-negligible at the periodic boundary (which would introduce
     aliasing errors due to the mismatch between the periodic FFT
     boundary condition and the confining trap).

Authors : [Author names]
Journal : [Target journal]
Date    : 2025
"""

